    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>How Can Musicians Protect Their Art?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Eric Laufer letter points out that groups such as Grateful Dead and Phish have been allowing fans to distribute music among themselves for free for years</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Freedom, One Song at a Time'' by Clay Shirky (Op-Ed, July 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Freedom, One Song at a Time'' by Clay Shirky (Op-Ed, July 15):</p>
        <p>As an unsigned professional musician, I have been paying close attention to the hubbub over Napster. No one is denying that the Napster software, which allows fans to freely distribute music among themselves, has great potential as a marketing tool for musicians. In fact, the Grateful Dead, and more recently Phish, have been allowing their fans to do exactly this for years.</p>
        <p>But it is not the fans' role to decide how the music is distributed. That is the musicians' right, and that of the company that helped pay for an album. Asserting that musicians shouldn't care about intellectual property rights because sales are up is a non sequitur.</p>
        <p>Music is art. Everyone should remember that there are some musicians who would rather have greater control of their art than more album sales.</p>
        <p>ERIC LAUFER  Setauket, N.Y., July 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
